### PR summary [32a9b396f0](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/15898/commits/32a9b396f05ca792ff0dd8b8bb88fa2cb3be83af)

#### Import changes for modified files

No significant changes to the import graph


<details><summary>Import changes for all files</summary>

|Files|Import difference|
|-|-|
| `Mathlib.autolabel` `Mathlib.Tactic`|1|
| `Mathlib.labels`|2|

</details>

---

<details><summary>

#### Declarations diff

</summary>

`+ Label`
`+ addAllLabels`
`+ findLabel?`
`+ formatIdsToDirs`
`+ getLast`
`+ labelsToFiles`
`+ produceLabels`
<details>
  <summary>You can run this locally as follows</summary>


```bash
## summary with just the declaration names:
./scripts/declarations_diff.sh <optional_commit>

## more verbose report:
./scripts/declarations_diff.sh long <optional_commit>
```
</details>

The doc-module for `script/declarations_diff.sh` contains some details about this script.

</details>

I was curious about your Lean rewrite of the autolabel script, so I took a look already. I hope you don't mind! (Let me know if you prefer to just hack on it instead.)

Your new script looks really shiny and elaborate. In my mind, I was thinking of something much simpler (basically, a direct port as much as possible), hence I wonder if all this complexity is necessary. (It is really fun to *write* this, I agree --- but as code is read more often, I care about future readers more...) As far as I can see, the drivers of that complexity are
(1) adding exclusions (to handle Tactic.Lint getting labelled as t-linter, but Tactic.Simp as t-meta)
(2) ensuring "Algebra/File.lean" does not get labelled "t-algebraic-geometry"
(Can you handle this by using the `Name` API more? I presume it has all the logic with prefixes already...)
(3) allowing for multi-level inclusions in a general way
(4) separating the core logic and the mapping, which implies an environment extension, macros to manipulate this list etc.

The shell script dealt with these by
- performing one preprocessing step to handle "Tactic/Linter", and
- doing a simple matching of root directory to label name
- disallowing multi-part directories, other than that
- defining both the mapping and the logic in the same script.

I wonder if the new script's complexity is already necessary. (That said, reading this in detail will be a good way for me to learn more about Lean programming.)

I do like the self-tests, these are great. Another thought I had was validating the script's configuration. Because it's all in Lean, you can check for typos (e.g. "." vs "/"), warn if the label rules and the root directories on disk do not match (on both directions), etc. this *is* much nicer than in shell, and definitely useful.

This PR contains both the shell script and the lean one: I am closing this, since there are two separate PRs now, one with the lean script (#15938) and one with the shell script (#15848, probably closed in favour of the Lean one).
